## Project Objective

Build a companion web site to the print materials produced in the Page
Layout class. Use the same branding (color palette, type of imagery,
fonts, overall aesthetics) as the print project.



## HTML Overview

1.  Use the [improved Emmet shortcut (in Tips & Tricks on
    LEA)](tips-tricks.md#basic-html-template-improved) to generate
    your html template.

2.  Add all the links (css reset, css style, google font, main
    navigation and footer navigation) to the template.

3.  Top navigation has SVGs just like the ap-nav exercise. Remember to
    add text links (in a span tag) like: \<span\>home\</span\>.

4.  Footer navigation **is the same links as the main navigation but
    without the SVGs**.

5.  Once this template is complete, duplicate it several times. Rename
    it to the names of the pages you need. Last one will be contact.md

6.  Test your navigation and fix as necessary.

7.  Copy the texts from InDesign. Page 1 in InDesign is index.md

8.  All page content goes into the \<main\> tag. Everything else
    (header, nav, footer, etc) is identical on every page (except the
    location of the currentpage class in the navigation).

9.  Within \<main\>, you will probably use only h1, h2, p, img and maybe
    ul tags. All things we have done this semester.



## 1. Technical Requirements & Evaluation Criteria 

### 1.1 Technical Requirements 

-   Mobile first design

    -   Design at 320px
    -   Desktop is only a bonus

-   Minimum 5 page web site

    -   Home
    -   Contact
    -   3 others according to subject

-   Valid HTML on each page

    -   Validate often
    -   Standard block elements
        -   header
        -   nav
        -   main (main content)
        -   aside (secondary content)
        -   footer

-   Elements stacked top-to-bottom

    -   Use **margins** to space them apart

-   Navigation bar with custom SVG icons (with text links underneath)

-   Minimum 2 photos per page

    -   img tag
    -   alt text
    -   resized pixel dimensions
    -   saved as optimized jpeg
    -   transparent images saved as optimized png-24

-   Valid CSS in an external stylesheet

    -   Validate often
    -   Minimum 2 background images
    -   Use rem/em/%, avoid px

-   Google (or Adobe) font for headers (h1-h6) and another for body text

### 1.2 Evaluation Criteria 

#### Technical Requirements 

1.  All HTML pages must be valid
2.  CSS stylesheet must be valid
3.  No lateral scroll on mobile
4.  Images are resized
5.  Custom font family is required

### Artistic Requirements

1.  Margin, spacing and negative space
2.  Alignment

### 1.3 Bonus (+10%) 

-   Desktop design (60rem media query)
-   Wrapper div
-   Use display: flex to place elements side-by-side



## 2. How to Start 

### Basics

-   Set your browser to mobile preview at 320px wide.
-   Start at the top and work your way down.

### Head Tag

-   Add any Google (or Adobe fonts) to the \<head\> tag. See \"[design
    considerations](./design-considerations.md)\" document on LEA for
    a link to the Adobe help page for adding Adobe fonts.

### Header

-   Add a logo and slogan to the header
    -   Required: Size the logo
    -   Required: add alt text to every image (describe the content of
        the image for people who cannot see it)
    -   Required: Define the font, font-size and color of the company
        name/slogan.
    -   Required: Adjust margins and padding (logo should not touch the
        edge of the header (if it is visible, ie has a borer and/or
        background color), nor the edge of the screen).
    -   Required: Adjust margin bottom (between header and navigation).
    -   Option: Add a background color
    -   Option: Add a border
    -   Option: Add a background image(s)

### Top Navigation

-   Add all links to the top navigation
    -   Required: Add pagename.md to the href=\"\".
    -   Required: Add the page name inside the span tag.
    -   Required: Link or add the SVG code for the icons inside each
        \<a\> tag.
        -   You can use a \<img src=\"img/icon-name.svg\"\> tag to link
            to an SVG inside the img folder
        -   Or you can copy/paste the SVG code into the HTML page.
        -   Only difference is that you can control the stroke/fill
            colors of the SVG only if it is pasted in the HTML.
            Otherwise, the SVG appears as in Illustrator and cannot be
            changed by CSS when linked to.
    -   In the CSS, give the .icon class a width (refer to previous
        exercises for sample code).
    -   Add another class name (after icon) to each link (ex: home,
        contact, etc). See previous exercises as a reference.

### Bottom Navigation

-   Add all the same links to the bottom navigation
    -   Same links as at the top, **but without icons**.

### Main Tag

-   Add the text and img tags inside the \<main\> tag.
-   Most texts will be in \<h1\>, \<h2\> or \<p\> tags. Some may be in
    \<ul\> or \<ol\> lists.

### Images

-   Add all content images to the \<img\> folder.
-   Required: add alt text to every image (describe the content of the
    image for people who cannot see it)
-   Images used by the CSS should be saved in the \<img\> folder within
    the theme folder.



## 3. HTML: Use the Emmet Shortcuts Provided 

-   Each page uses the same HTML skeleton.
-   Use the Emmet abbreviation below to first create index.md.
    -   Add the logo
    -   Company name/slogan
    -   All the links (same links in top navigation and bottom

-   Then duplicate index.md several times to create the four other

## 4. CSS DESIGN STEPS

1.  Use margins to space elements apart from each other vertically (most
    important on mobile! use margin top and bottom).

2.  Use margins left and right to keep things from touching the edge of
    the screen.

3.  You can use padding instead of margins. For example: instead of
    adding margins left and right on every tag inside \<main\>, just
    give main some left and right padding instead. In other words, give
    padding to the parent element rather than to each child
    individually. Faster. Easier.

4.  Once the pages are built and the page layout works (margins!) add:

-   background colors (opaque or semi-transparent rgba)

-   background image (single or multiple)

-   optional: you can use absolute positioning to place the nav items
    within the menu

-   if you use absolute positioning for the nav icons (.icon class) add
    \"position: relative\" to the #menu (see social icons and sunthing
    for working examples)

16. Everything you need to do is in the assignments you uploaded to your
    server during the semester. Look at your old work to see how you did
    things.

17. If you used my template, the pop up nav/hamburger icon code I handed
    out today should just work. Add the button and id to your html
    pages. Add the css as is to your style.css file.

If you have any issues, just send me a MIO. Add your project as a zip
attachment.

3.  [Google](https://www.duckduckgo.com) things!
4.  Look at sites and **inspect their code**



## 6. Colors and Fonts 
-   Use the same colors and fonts as what you are using in InDesign.
-   Make sure your CMYK print colors are converted to RGB colors for web
    use (see [convert the colors to RGB
    colorspace](https://colordesigner.io/convert/cmyktorgb){target="_blank"}).
-   If you use Adobe fonts in InDesign, see [the Design considerations
    document for instructions](./design-considerations.md#adobe-fonts)
    on how to use Adobe fonts in a web project.
-   Otherwise, you are basically just trying to match the overall \"look
    and feel\" of the print document in web (even if they aren\'t
    identical, they look related).



## 7. Validate your HTML and CSS often 

-   Make sure you have the **W3C Web Validator** VS Code extension
    installed.
-   **Validate the CSS very often. Even minor mistakes can create big
    problems.**
